# Nuxt 4 + Vue 3 Standards

Follow the official [Nuxt 4 docs](https://nuxt.com/docs) and Vue 3 best practices. Keep code simple and readable.

## Components

- Always use `<script setup lang="ts">` — never the Options API.
- Type props/emits with `defineProps<...>()` / `defineEmits<...>()`.
- Prefer single-responsibility components; extract logic into composables.

```vue
<!-- ✅ GOOD -->
<script setup lang="ts">
const props = defineProps<{ title: string }>()
const { count, increment } = useCounter()
</script>

<!-- ❌ BAD: Options API -->
<script lang="ts">
export default { data() { return { count: 0 } } }
</script>
```

## Composables

- Reusable logic goes in `app/composables/` as `useXxx.ts`.
- Auto-imported by Nuxt — do not import manually.
- Return refs/computed/methods as a plain object.

```ts
// app/composables/useCounter.ts
export const useCounter = () => {
  const count = ref(0)
  const increment = () => count.value++
  return { count, increment }
}
```

## State Management

- Prefer composables + `useState()` for shared state (Nuxt's SSR-safe ref).
- Use Pinia stores **only if `pinia` / `@pinia/nuxt` is installed** in `package.json`. Otherwise stick with composables.

## TypeScript

- Strict typing — avoid `any`. Use `unknown` + narrowing when needed.
- Type API responses via generics on `$fetch<T>()` / `useFetch<T>()`.

## Nuxt Conventions

- Use built-ins: `useFetch`, `useAsyncData`, `useRoute`, `useRuntimeConfig`, `navigateTo`.
- Pages live in `app/pages/`, layouts in `app/layouts/`, components in `app/components/`.
- Rely on auto-imports for composables and components — keep imports minimal.
